Chapter 2: Mathematical Preliminaries — Enriched Categories, Information Geometry, and Type Theory

2.1 Enriched Category Theory over Quantales

Definition 2.1 (Quantale). A quantale \mathcal{V} = (V, \leq, \otimes, I) is a complete lattice (V, \leq) with a monoidal structure (\otimes, I) such that \otimes distributes over arbitrary joins.

Example 2.2 (Cost Quantale). \mathcal{V} = ([0,\infty], \geq, +, 0) where:

· Order: a \leq b iff a \geq b (reverse order for costs);
· Monoidal product: a \otimes b = a + b;
· Unit: I = 0;
· Joins: \bigvee S = \inf S (greatest lower bound in usual order).

Definition 2.3 (\mathcal{V}-Enriched Category). A category \mathcal{C} enriched over \mathcal{V} consists of:

· A class \text{Ob}(\mathcal{C}) of objects;
· For each A,B \in \text{Ob}(\mathcal{C}), a hom-object \mathcal{C}(A,B) \in V;
· Composition morphisms: \mathcal{C}(B,C) \otimes \mathcal{C}(A,B) \to \mathcal{C}(A,C) satisfying associativity;
· Identity elements: I \to \mathcal{C}(A,A) satisfying unit laws.

Proposition 2.4 (Metric Spaces as Enriched Categories). A generalized metric space (X,d) with d: X \times X \to [0,\infty] satisfying d(x,x)=0 and d(x,z) \leq d(x,y)+d(y,z) is precisely a category enriched over ([0,\infty], \geq, +, 0).

Proof. Take objects as points, hom-object d(x,y), composition given by triangle inequality, and identity d(x,x)=0. ∎

2.2 Information Geometry with Curvature Analysis

Definition 2.5 (Sectional Curvature). For a Riemannian manifold (\mathcal{M}, g) and a 2-plane \Pi \subset T_p\mathcal{M} spanned by orthonormal vectors u,v, the sectional curvature is:

\sec(\Pi) = R(u,v,u,v)

where R is the Riemann curvature tensor.

Theorem 2.6 (Rauch Comparison). If \sec(\mathcal{M}) \geq \kappa, then geodesic triangles in \mathcal{M} are “thinner” than comparison triangles in the space form of constant curvature \kappa. Conversely, if \sec \leq \kappa, triangles are “fatter”.

Consequences for optimization: For geodesically convex functions, gradient descent converges with rate dependent on curvature bounds (see [Zhang & Sra 2016]).

Proposition 2.7 (Curvature and Optimization). Let \mathcal{F} be geodesically convex and L-smooth on (\mathcal{M},g).

· If \sec \geq 0: gradient descent converges with rate O(1/t).
· If \sec \leq -\kappa < 0: exponential convergence possible, but step-size must be bounded by 1/(L+\kappa).
· If |\sec| \leq K: stability bounds depend on K and dimension.

2.3 Dependent Type Theory and Hoare Logic

Definition 2.8 (Refinement Type). Given a type A and predicate \varphi: A \to \text{Prop}, the refinement type is:

\{x : A \mid \varphi(x)\}

with introduction rule: if \Gamma \vdash t : A and \Gamma \vdash \varphi(t) then \Gamma \vdash t : \{x:A \mid \varphi(x)\}.

Definition 2.9 (Hoare Triple). For precondition P, program c, postcondition Q:

\{P\} c \{Q\}

means: if P holds before executing c, then Q holds after (if c terminates).

Proposition 2.10 (Curry–Howard for Beliefs). Under the proofs-as-programs correspondence:

· Belief states q \in \mathcal{M} correspond to terms of type \mathcal{M};
· Safety invariants \varphi(q) correspond to propositions;
· Belief updates \mathfrak{I}(q) correspond to functions preserving proofs: (q : \{x:\mathcal{M} \mid \varphi(x)\}) \to \mathfrak{I}(q) : \{y:\mathcal{M} \mid \varphi(y)\}.

