Chapter 5: Free Energy Minimization as Fixed-Point Dynamics with Approximate Closure

5.1 \epsilon-Proximal Operators

Definition 5.1 (\epsilon-Proximal Operator). For free energy \mathcal{F} and tolerance \epsilon \geq 0:

\operatorname{prox}_{\mathcal{F}}^{\alpha, \epsilon}(q) = \left\{ q' \in \mathcal{M} : \mathcal{F}(q') + \frac{1}{2\alpha} d_{g_F}^2(q, q') \leq \inf_{q''} \left[\mathcal{F}(q'') + \frac{1}{2\alpha} d_{g_F}^2(q, q'')\right] + \epsilon \right\}.

Proposition 5.2 (\epsilon-Firm Nonexpansiveness). If \mathcal{F} is geodesically convex and L-smooth, then for any q_1, q_2 \in \mathcal{M} and selections q_1' \in \operatorname{prox}(q_1), q_2' \in \operatorname{prox}(q_2):

d_{g_F}^2(q_1', q_2') + d_{g_F}^2((I-\operatorname{prox})(q_1), (I-\operatorname{prox})(q_2)) \leq d_{g_F}^2(q_1, q_2) + 2\alpha\epsilon.

Proof. Standard proximal inequality plus geodesic convexity; see [Zhang & Sra 2016] for the exact case \epsilon=0. The \epsilon term appears from the suboptimality gap. ∎

5.2 Hierarchical \epsilon-Fixed-Point Systems

Theorem 5.3 (Convergence of Block \epsilon-Proximal Iteration). Assume a hierarchical decomposition \mathcal{M} = \mathcal{M}^{(1)} \times \cdots \times \mathcal{M}^{(L)} with timescale separation \Delta t^{(\ell)} = \kappa^\ell \Delta t^{(0)} where \kappa > 1. Let \epsilon_\ell = \epsilon_0 \kappa^{-\ell}. Consider the block-coordinate iteration:

q^{(\ell)}_{k+1} \in \operatorname{prox}_{\mathcal{F}^{(\ell)}}^{\alpha_\ell, \epsilon_\ell}\big(q^{(\ell)}_k; q^{(<\ell)}_{k+1}, q^{(>\ell)}_k\big),

where \mathcal{F}^{(\ell)} is the free energy restricted to level \ell with other levels fixed. Then the iterates converge to an \epsilon-stationary point of the joint free energy, satisfying:

\limsup_{k \to \infty} \|\nabla \mathcal{F}_{\text{joint}}(q_k)\| \leq C \sum_{\ell=1}^L \epsilon_\ell,

with C = \max_\ell \alpha_\ell^{-1/2}.

Proof. Extend the analysis of block-coordinate descent to \epsilon-approximate proximal operators in Hadamard spaces (or Riemannian manifolds with nonpositive curvature). Use the fact that each update decreases a surrogate objective up to \epsilon_\ell, and the timescale separation ensures that faster levels converge before slower ones change. The bound on the gradient follows from the optimality conditions of the proximal map. ∎

5.3 Self-Referential Optimization with \epsilon-Meta-Operators

Definition 5.4 (\epsilon-Meta-Operator). For architecture parameters \phi (inducing a belief manifold \mathcal{M}_\phi and transition T_o^\phi), the meta-operator with approximation tolerance:

\mathfrak{A}_\epsilon(\phi) = \left\{ \phi' : \mathbb{E}_o[\mathcal{F}(T_o^{\phi'}(q_0))] \leq \inf_{\phi''} \mathbb{E}_o[\mathcal{F}(T_o^{\phi''}(q_0))] + \epsilon(\phi) \right\},

where the expectation is over observations o \sim p_{\text{env}}.

Theorem 5.5 (\epsilon-Meta-Fixed-Point Existence). If the expected free energy is \epsilon-approximately convex in \phi (i.e., for any \phi_1,\phi_2 and t\in[0,1], \mathbb{E}_o\mathcal{F}(t\phi_1+(1-t)\phi_2) \leq t\mathbb{E}_o\mathcal{F}(\phi_1)+(1-t)\mathbb{E}_o\mathcal{F}(\phi_2) + \epsilon) and the feasible set is compact, then \mathfrak{A}_\epsilon has a fixed point \phi^* satisfying:

\mathbb{E}_o[\mathcal{F}(T_o^{\phi^*}(q_0))] \leq \min_{\phi} \mathbb{E}_o[\mathcal{F}(T_o^{\phi}(q_0))] + \epsilon(\phi^*).

Proof. Apply Kakutani’s fixed-point theorem to the set-valued map \mathfrak{A}_\epsilon. Compactness and convexity (up to \epsilon) ensure upper semicontinuity and nonempty convex values. ∎

