Chapter 8: Existence, Uniqueness, and Convergence Theorems for \epsilon-Monadic Systems

8.1 \epsilon-Viscosity Solutions

Definition 8.1 (\epsilon-Viscosity Subsolution). A continuous function u: \mathcal{M} \to \mathbb{R} is an \epsilon-viscosity subsolution of the Hamilton–Jacobi–Bellman equation H(x,u,Du)=0 if for any \phi \in C^1 such that u-\phi has a local maximum at x_0:

H(x_0, u(x_0), D\phi(x_0)) \leq \epsilon.

Theorem 8.2 (\epsilon-Comparison Principle). If H is proper and uniformly continuous, and u is an \epsilon_1-subsolution and v an \epsilon_2-supersolution satisfying boundary conditions, then:

\sup_{\mathcal{M}} (u-v) \leq \sup_{\partial\mathcal{M}} (u-v)^+ + C(\epsilon_1 + \epsilon_2),

where C depends on the Lipschitz constant of H.

Proof. Standard viscosity solution comparison argument (see e.g. Crandall, Ishii, Lions 1992), with additional terms from the \epsilon slack. ∎

8.2 Hierarchical \epsilon-Banach Theorem

Theorem 8.3 (\epsilon-Hierarchical Fixed Point). Let \mathcal{X}_\ell be complete metric spaces, and let T^{(\ell)}: \mathcal{X}_1 \times \cdots \times \mathcal{X}_L \to \mathcal{X}_\ell be \epsilon_\ell-contractions in the following sense: there exist constants \kappa_\ell < 1 and \delta_\ell \geq 0 such that for any x,y:

d_\ell(T^{(\ell)}(x), T^{(\ell)}(y)) \leq \kappa_\ell d_\ell(x_\ell, y_\ell) + \delta_\ell \sum_{j \neq \ell} d_j(x_j, y_j) + \epsilon_\ell.

Define the composite operator T(x) = (T^{(1)}(x),\dots,T^{(L)}(x)). If

\prod_{\ell=1}^L (\kappa_\ell + \delta_\ell) \cdot \Gamma < 1,

where \Gamma is a coupling constant (e.g., the maximum number of dependencies), then T has a unique \epsilon-fixed point x^* satisfying:

d(x^*, T(x^*)) \leq \frac{\sum_\ell \epsilon_\ell}{1 - \prod_\ell (\kappa_\ell + \delta_\ell)\Gamma}.

Proof. Construct a contraction on the product space with the weighted metric d(x,y) = \sum_\ell w_\ell d_\ell(x_\ell,y_\ell) chosen to absorb the coupling. The \epsilon terms accumulate via the triangle inequality. ∎

8.3 Resource-Aware Verification Convergence

Theorem 8.4 (Projected Flow with Proof Generation). Under the assumptions of Theorem 7.6 and if proof generation time for a safety invariant \varphi (expressed as a polynomial inequality) is O(\operatorname{poly}(\dim, \log(1/\delta))) for error tolerance \delta (using quantifier elimination or SMT), then with probability at least 1-\delta:

· The algorithm converges to an \epsilon-optimal architecture;
· All returned belief states satisfy safety invariants with proof certificates;
· Total runtime is O(\operatorname{poly}(1/\epsilon, \log(1/\delta))).

Proof. Combine the convergence rate of the optimization with the probabilistic guarantees of the prover. The probability that any update fails to produce a proof within resource bounds is bounded by \delta via union bound. ∎

