Appendix C: Proof of the Optimal Curvature Theorem (Full)

We provide a complete proof of Theorem 4.3, filling in the details of the trade-off functional and the existence of the optimal interval.

Theorem 4.3 (Optimal Curvature). Let \mathcal{M} be a complete Riemannian manifold with sectional curvature bounded |\sec| \leq K_0. Consider geodesic stochastic gradient descent (SGD) minimizing a geodesically convex, L-smooth free energy \mathcal{F}:\mathcal{M}\to\mathbb{R} with step size \eta_t = 1/(tL) for \kappa_{\min} \geq 0 (or constant \eta = 1/(L+K_0) for negative curvature). Then:

1. If \kappa_{\min} > 0 (positive curvature), the convergence rate is exponential: \mathbb{E}[\mathcal{F}(q_t) - \mathcal{F}^*] \leq C_1 e^{-\lambda t} with \lambda = \eta \kappa_{\min}, but the sample complexity to reach \epsilon-accuracy is \Omega(e^{c \kappa_{\max} \operatorname{diam}(\mathcal{M})}) for some c>0.
2. If \kappa_{\max} < 0 (negative curvature), the sample complexity is O(\log(1/\epsilon)) (dimension-free), but convergence requires adaptive step sizes and may exhibit chaotic transients; the rate is at most O(1/t).
3. There exists an optimal interval [\kappa_{\min}^*, \kappa_{\max}^*] containing 0 such that the product of convergence rate (inverse time to reach \epsilon) and sample complexity is minimized. Moreover, this interval can be chosen within [-K_0, K_0].

Proof. We break the proof into several parts.

C.1 Preliminaries on Geodesic SGD

Let q_t be the iterate of SGD on \mathcal{M} with stochastic gradient g_t(q_t) = \nabla \mathcal{F}(q_t) + \xi_t, where \xi_t is zero-mean noise with bounded variance. The update is q_{t+1} = \exp_{q_t}(-\eta_t g_t(q_t)). Standard results (see Zhang & Sra 2016) give, under geodesic convexity and L-smoothness,

\mathbb{E}[\mathcal{F}(q_{t+1}) - \mathcal{F}^*] \leq (1 - 2\eta_t \mu) \mathbb{E}[\mathcal{F}(q_t) - \mathcal{F}^*] + \frac{\eta_t^2 L \sigma^2}{2},

