Appendix D: Dependent Type Theory and Hoare Logic for Beliefs

D.1 Refinement Types for Belief Manifolds

Let \mathcal{M} be a belief manifold. A safety invariant \varphi is a predicate on \mathcal{M} expressible in the language of real closed fields (e.g., polynomial inequalities). The refinement type

\{q: \mathcal{M} \mid \varphi(q)\}

denotes the subset of \mathcal{M} where \varphi holds. In a proof assistant, this is implemented as a dependent pair (sigma type).

Typing Rules:

\frac{\Gamma \vdash q : \mathcal{M} \quad \Gamma \vdash \varphi(q) : \text{Prop}}{\Gamma \vdash q : \{x:\mathcal{M} \mid \varphi(x)\}} \quad \text{(if $\varphi(q)$ is provable)}

\frac{\Gamma \vdash q : \{x:\mathcal{M} \mid \varphi(x)\}}{\Gamma \vdash q : \mathcal{M}} \quad \text{(subtyping)}

D.2 Hoare Logic for Belief Updates

A belief update is a function \text{update}: \mathcal{M} \times \mathcal{O} \to \mathcal{M}. To express safety, we use Hoare triples:

\{\varphi(q)\} \ \text{update}(q,o) \ \{\varphi(q')\}

meaning: if \varphi(q) holds before the update, then after the update \varphi(q') holds (assuming termination).

Proof Rule for Composition:

\frac{\{\varphi\} c_1 \{\psi\} \quad \{\psi\} c_2 \{\chi\}}{\{\varphi\} c_1;c_2 \{\chi\}}

Proof Rule for Loops (with invariant): For a while loop, we need an invariant I such that \{I \land b\} c \{I\} and I \land \neg b \Rightarrow \chi.

D.3 Proof Terms

Under the Curry–Howard correspondence, a proof of \{\varphi\} c \{\psi\} is a function that takes a proof of \varphi (and any inputs) and returns a proof of \psi along with the output state. Formally, if we view c as a function of type \Pi q:\mathcal{M}. \mathcal{O} \to \mathcal{M}, then a verified update has type:

\Pi q: \{x:\mathcal{M} \mid \varphi(x)\}. \Pi o:\mathcal{O}. \{y:\mathcal{M} \mid \psi(y)\}.

This is exactly the dependent function type we used in Definition 6.1.

D.4 Soundness of Deferred Verification

Let \text{Upd}(q,o,R) return a pair (q', \pi) where \pi is either a proof term or a deferred token. The runtime checker, when presented with a deferred token, can either wait for the background prover or verify a cached proof. If the background prover is sound, any proof it produces is valid. If the runtime checker itself checks the proof (e.g., by evaluating a verified decision procedure), then we have:

Theorem (Soundness). For any execution of Algorithm 6.4, if the output is marked "verified", then \varphi(q') holds. If a deferred proof is later found invalid, the system raises an alarm.

Proof. By induction on the steps. The base case uses the assumption that the initial belief satisfies \varphi. For the update step, if a proof is generated, it is checked by the runtime (or by the prover's soundness). If deferred, the background prover will eventually produce a proof or a counterexample; in the latter case, the system detects the violation. ∎

